A firewall protects a system by controlling network traffic based on predefined security rules. It examines every incoming and outgoing packet and decides whether to allow, block, or reject it.

âœ… Core Steps in Firewall Traffic Filtering
1. Packet Inspection

The firewall analyzes each packetâ€™s:

Source & destination IP addresses

Port numbers (e.g., 22, 80, 443)

Protocol type (TCP/UDP/ICMP)

Packet state (NEW, ESTABLISHED, RELATED)

2. Rule Matching

Traffic is compared against a rule set:

ALLOW â†’ Packet is allowed through

DENY/BLOCK â†’ Packet is dropped

DEFAULT POLICY â†’ Used when no rule matches

Rules are processed top to bottom.

3. Direction-Based Filtering

Firewalls filter traffic depending on where itâ€™s going:

Inbound traffic â†’ Coming into the system

Outbound traffic â†’ Leaving the system

Example:
Blocking inbound Telnet (port 23) while allowing outbound web traffic.

4. Port & Service Control

Firewalls can allow or block traffic for specific services:

Open port â†’ Service reachable

Blocked port â†’ Service inaccessible

Example:
ufw allow 22/tcp â†’ Allows SSH
ufw deny 23/tcp â†’ Blocks Telnet

5. Stateful Filtering

Modern firewalls track active connections:

Automatically allow return traffic

Block unsolicited or suspicious packets

This prevents attacks like spoofing or random connection attempts.

6. Logging & Monitoring

Firewalls log allowed/blocked traffic to help:

Detect intrusions

Debug connectivity issues

Audit security activity

Example:
Linux UFW log: /var/log/ufw.log

